These are the first two volumes of a new journal pub­lished in Australia under the joint editorship of Ian Farrington and Rodolfo Raffino with a multinational editorial board made up of an impressive number of Inka scholars. Dedicated to papers on the Prehispanic Inka, pre-lnka period, and early Colonial era of the Andean region, Tiwantinsuyu promises coverage of archaeology, ethnohistory, physical anthropology, lin­guistics, religion, ecology, and archaeoastronomy by scholars working in Ecuador, Bolivia, Argentina, Chile, and Peru. The journal will print articles in either Spanish or English. The stated intent of the editors is to include a long abstract in the other language, although that goal was not fully realized in the first two issues. In addition to general articles, both volumes also pub­lished book reviews. The second volume initiated a new feature: a review of recent discoveries and investi­gations of the Inka empire. Readers are encouraged to send short contributions for this feature. 
